,Recommended,268220,10392635,"Posted: 8 June, 2014",all,GamerOnline,"Arcade tactical combat at it's finest. Surprisingly good for a mobile port to the PC, the gameplay is good for what it is and the graphics are stylized and work well.Combat appears simple, though it requires thought and strategy. Sometimes taking cover and shooting works well, other times running and gunning (with rolling and dodging) is best. It all depends on what's shooting or throwing grenades at you, or self destructs (scary). Different weapons (and armor) for different situations, which are unlocked for purchase by meeting various criteria. You can carry up to two weapons at once and switch on the fly. Various upgrades are also available for purchase once sufficient funds and upgrade chips are collected.Upgrade your skills as you level up. There are three branches: Specialist, Soldier and Medic. Each one has features and bonuses appropriate for it's type. Choose which ones you want first to fit your play style or adapt it as you see fit (you get all of them eventually). Skills can be reset for the right price. Weapon upgrades can also be reset, you get nine points to allocate amongst two sequential branches and are a bit more limited. With weapons, resetting is free (at the time of this writing).Mystery boxes (bonus items) which appear to be randomly dropped as loot, contain assorted items such as Extra Credits, Extra Experience, Upgrade Chips, One Ups (extra lives/continues) and the dreaded...Nothing! These boxes are opened after level completion, if you survive. Add in looted powerups such as Double Damage (a brief damage spree) and Nuke 'Em (damages all nearby enemies on pick-up) for extra fun and mayhem. Replay levels to improve your rating (up to three stars). Steam achievements (collect 'em all) and trading cards included.__Notes: This review is based on the reviewer's single player experience (finished level 30 in a bit over 10 hours). Multi-player has not yet been attempted. No game crashes were encountered although some issues with the game interface (weapon unlocks) have been noted while playing with a gamepad and require a mouse to respond."
